1 e. Temporary and permanent nuclear waste storage, including in-state and out-of-
2 state siting locations;
3 f. Small modular and micro nuclear reactors, including the feasibility of constructing
4 and operating small modular and micro reactors to generate power in the state;
5 and
6 g. Provisions of the North Dakota Century Code that place restrictions on advanced
7 nuclear energy development, if any.
8 2. The study must invite participation from an institution of higher education for
9 assistance in evaluating social interests and community acceptance of potential siting
10 locations.
11 3. The committee must consist of:
12 a. Two members representing the energy industry, appointed by the legislative
13 management;
14 b. One member appointed by the public service commission;
15 c. One member appointed by the industrial commission;
16 d. One member appointed by the director of the department of water resources;
17 e. Three members of the house of representatives selected by the majority leader of
18 the house of representatives, two of whom must represent the majority faction of
19 the house of representatives and one of whom must represent the minority
20 faction of the house of representatives; and
21 f. Three members of the senate selected by the majority leader of the senate, two
22 of whom must represent the majority faction of the senate and one of whom must
23 represent the minority faction of the senate.
24 4. The legislative management shall report its findings and recommendations, together
25 with any legislation required to implement the recommendations, to the seventieth
26 legislative assembly.
27 5. a. A member of the committee who is not a state employee is entitled to
28 reimbursement for mileage and expenses as provided by law for state officers
29 and employees, to be paid by the legislative council.
